value.value: A RASopathy characterized by unusually sparse, brittle, curly hair, macrocephaly, a prominent forehead and bi-temporal narrowing, intellectual disability, failure to thrive, congenital heart defects, short stature and skin abnormalities, and has_material_basis_in mutation in the BRAF, MAP2K1, MAP2kK2 and KRAS genes.
An acrocephalosyndactylia characterized by craniosynostosis, acrocephaly, obesity, syndactyly and polydactyly.
A lipid metabolism disorder characterized by an enzymatic defect that prevents long-chain fatty acids from being transported into the mitochondria.
A purine-pyrimidine metabolic disorder characterized by deficiency of xanthine oxidase, resulting in excretion of large amounts of xanthine in the urine and the formation of xanthine stones.
A syndrome characterized by severe intellectual disability, microcephaly, congenital cataract, microcornea, microphthalmia, agenesis or hypoplasia of the corpus callosum and hypogenitalism.

A syndrome characterized by facial abnormalities such as telecanthus, epicanthus, broad flattened nose, large inverted W-shaped mouth and malformed ears, malformed extremities such as camptodactyly, clinodactyly, interdigital webbing and joint hyperlaxity and mental retardation.
A syndrome characterized by the combination of lower lip pits, cleft lip with or without cleft palate and cleft palate alone.
A skin disease characterized by photosensitivity and liver spots (solar lentigines).
A syndrome characterized by dwarfism, facial dysmorphia and skeletal abnormalities.
A syndactyly characterized by an increased number of digits; often a result of a mutation in the HOXD13 gene.
An articulation disorder characterized by involuntary sound repetition and disruption or blocking of speech.
A language disorder characterized by difficulty in language acquisition despite otherwise normal development and in the absence of any obvious explanatory factors.
A hereditary spastic paraplegia associated with dementia.

A hereditary spastic paraplegia that is characterized by hydrocephalus, spasticity of the lower limbs, adducted thumbs, aphasia, seizures, agenesis of the corpus callosum and intellectual disability in the mild to moderate range.
A Dyggve-Melchior-Clausen disease that is characterized by short limbs and a short trunk with a barrel-shaped chest.

A syndrome characterized by pre- and postnatal overgrowth and craniofacial, skeletal, cardiac and renal abnormalities and has_material_basis_in mutation in the gene encoding glypican-3 (GPC3) on chromosome Xq26.
A bone structure disease characterized by an appreciable lateral deviation in the normally straight vertical line of the spine.
A scoliosis with no known cause.
A hyperostosis characterized by excessive bone formation most prominent in the skull, mandible, clavicle, ribs and diaphyses of long bones; bone formation occurs throughout life.
A corneal disease in which the cornea blends with sclera, resulting in clouding of the cornea.
A muscular dystrophy which begins at the lower legs and affects the shoulder region earlier and more severely than distal arm.
A syndrome characterized by mild to moderate short stature due to growth delays after birth, distinctive craniofacial abnormalities, skeletal malformations and genital abnormalities.
A muscle tissue disease characterized by mechanically triggered contractions of skeletal muscle and that has_material_basis_in mutation in the caveolin-3 gene (CAV3) on chromosome 3p25.
A pigmentation disease characterized by a reticulate pattern of abnormally dark skin coloring, particularly in the body's folds and creases.
A pigmentation disease characterized by progressively pigmented and depigmented macules, often mixed in a reticulate pattern, concentrated on the dorsal extremities.

A pigmentation disease characterized by lesions that initially arise as letiginous, hyperpigmented macules in a reticular pattern on the dorsal aspect of the hands and feet. Over time, lesions may spread proximally and may darken; palmoplantar pitting and dermatoglyphic disruption may also be present.
A physical disorder characterized by pancreatic fibrosis, renal dysplasia and hepatic dysgenesis; it is usual fatal soon after birth.
An eye disease characterized by the drooping or falling of the upper or lower eyelid.
A ptosis characterized by eyelid drop present at birth.
A gastrointestinal system disease that is located_in the gallbladder.
A brain disease that is characterized by encephalomalacia and cystic brain lesions.
A neurodegenerative disease that is characterized by underdevelopment of the pons and cerebellum.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by central and peripheral motor dysfunction, hypotonia, spasticity and failure to thrive, has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VRK1 gene.

A severe pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by hypotonia, progressive microcephaly and developmental delay, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the EXOSC3 gene.

A severe pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, chorea, epilepsy and hyperreflexia, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the TSEN54 gene.

A severe pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, clonus, dysphagia and failure to thrive, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the TSEN2 gene.

A severe pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, extrapyramidal dyskinesia, seizure and failure to thrive, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the TSEN34 gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, profound intellectual disability, spasticity and seizure, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the SEPSECS gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, profound intellectual disability, spasticity and seizure, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the VPS53 gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, hypotonia, dysmorphic features, profound intellectual disability and seizure, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the PCLO gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, hypertonia, myoclonus, seizure and early lethality, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the TSEN54 gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by severe olivopontocerebellar hypoplasia and degeneration leading to early lethality, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the TSEN54 gene.
A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by olivopontocerebellar hypoplasia and developmental delay, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the RARS2 gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, hypotonia, gonadal abnormalities and respiratory failure, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive mutation in the TOE1 gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, chorea, hypotonia, spasticity and visual defects, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the CHMP1A gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by progressive microcephaly, spasticity, seizure and brain atrophy, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the AMPD2 gene.

A pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is characterized by severe developmental delays, progressive microcephaly, spasticity and seizure, has_material_basis_in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the CLP1 gene.
An adrenal cortex disease characterized by small to normal sized adrenal glands containing multiple small cortical pigmented nodules.
An epilepsy characterized by seizures triggered by visual stimuli that form patterns in space or time, such as flashing lights.

A developmental vitreous disease that is characterized by leukocoria, strabismus and vision loss, caused by failure of primary vitreous and hyaloid vasculature to regress during embryological development.
